@article{Elliot2003,
abstract = {We present a method for obtaining atmospheric temperature, pressure, and$\backslash$nnumber density profiles for small bodies through inversion of light$\backslash$ncurves recorded during stellar occultations. This method avoids the$\backslash$nassumption that the atmospheric scale height is small compared with the$\backslash$nradius of the body, and it includes the variation of gravitational$\backslash$nacceleration with radius. First we derive the integral equations for$\backslash$ntemperature, scale height, pressure, number density, refractivity, and$\backslash$nradius in terms of the light-curve flux. These are then cast into$\backslash$nsummation form suitable for numerical evaluation. Equations for the$\backslash$nerrors in these quantities caused by Gaussian noise in the occultation$\backslash$nlight curve are also derived. The method allows for an arbitrary$\backslash$natmospheric boundary condition above the inversion region, and one$\backslash$nparticular boundary condition is implemented through least-squares$\backslash$nfitting. When the inversion equations are applied to noiseless test data$\backslash$nfor a simulated isothermal atmosphere, numerical errors in the$\backslash$ncalculated temperature profile are less than 5 parts in 10(4).$\backslash$nNonisothermal test cases are also presented. We explore the effects of$\backslash$n(1) the boundary condition, ( 2) data averaging ( in the time,$\backslash$nobserver-plane, and body-plane domains), ( 3) systematic errors in the$\backslash$nzero stellar flux level, and (4) light-curve noise on the accuracy of$\backslash$nthe inversion results. A criterion is presented for deciding whether$\backslash$ninversion would be an appropriate analysis for a given stellar$\backslash$noccultation light curve, and limitations to the radial resolution of the$\backslash$ninversion results are discussed. The inversion method is then employed$\backslash$non the light curves for the 1988 June 9 occultation by Pluto observed$\backslash$nwith the Kuiper Airborne Observatory and the 1997 November 4 occultation$\backslash$nby Triton observed with the Hubble Space Telescope. Under the (possibly$\backslash$nincorrect) assumption that no extinction effects are present in the$\backslash$noccultation light curve, the Pluto inversion yields a 110 K isothermal$\backslash$npro. le down to approximately 1215 km radius, at which point a strong$\backslash$nthermal gradient, 3.9 +/- 0.6 K km(-1), abruptly appears, reaching 93 K$\backslash$nat the end of the inversion. The Triton inversion yields a differently$\backslash$nshaped profile, which has an upper level thermal gradient, similar to0.4$\backslash$nK km(-1), followed by a similar to 51 K isothermal pro. le at lower$\backslash$naltitudes. The Triton inversion shows wavelike temperature variations in$\backslash$nthe lower atmosphere, with amplitudes of similar to 1 K and wavelengths$\backslash$nof similar to 20 km, that could be caused by horizontal or vertical$\backslash$natmospheric waves.},
