tudes. Below the 0.4-mbar level all mass mixing ratio profiles increase with height. Above this pressure level, the profiles at 40°N, 45°N, 55°N, at the edge of the polar vortex, display a decrease-with-height whereas the other profiles increase. The global increase with height of the haze mass mixing ratio suggest a source at high altitudes and a sink at low altitudes. An enrichment of haze is observed at 0.1mbar around the equator, which could be due to a more efficient photochemistry because of the strongest insolation there or an accumulation of haze due to a balance between sedimentation and upward vertical drag. {\textcopyright} 2010 Elsevier Inc.},
author = {Vinatier, Sandrine and B{\'{e}}zard, Bruno and de Kok, Remco and Anderson, Carrie M. and Samuelson, Robert E. and Nixon, Conor A. and Mamoutkine, Andrei and Carlson, Ronald C. and Jennings, Donald E. and Guandique, Ever A. and Bjoraker, Gordon L. and {Michael Flasar}, F. and Kunde, Virgil G.},
